# Slack Bot

Connect a Slack app so people can run `/bg` and receive alerts in Slack. This page covers the
Slack-specific steps; for account linking, alert delivery, and the Admin UI /
environment-variable workflow that all platforms share, see [Chat Bots](/docs/bots).

## 1. Create a Slack app

1. Go to [api.slack.com/apps](https://api.slack.com/apps) and click **Create New App**.
2. Choose **From scratch**, name it (e.g. *Nocturne*), and pick the workspace to develop in.

## 2. Add bot scopes and install

1. Open **OAuth & Permissions**.
2. Under **Bot Token Scopes**, add the scopes the bot needs to post and respond, such as
   `chat:write`, `commands`, and `im:history`.
3. Click **Install to Workspace** and approve.
4. Copy the **Bot User OAuth Token** (it starts with `xoxb-`).

## 3. Collect the credentials

| Field | Where to find it |
|-------|------------------|
| **Bot Token** | **OAuth & Permissions** — the Bot User OAuth Token (`xoxb-…`) |
| **Signing Secret** | **Basic Information > App Credentials** |

## 4. Configure Nocturne

Enter both values using either method (see [Chat Bots](/docs/bots) for the full workflow).

### Option A: Admin UI

At **Settings > Admin > Integrations**, fill in the **Slack** card:

| Field | Value |
|-------|-------|
| **Bot Token** | The `xoxb-…` token from step 3 |
| **Signing Secret** | The signing secret from step 3 |

Turn **Enabled** on, click **Save**, and restart the Nocturne web service.

### Option B: Environment variables

```bash
SLACK_BOT_TOKEN=xoxb-...
SLACK_SIGNING_SECRET=...
```

Then restart Nocturne.

## 5. Point Slack at the webhook

Slack sends events, slash commands, and interactive actions to a single Request URL. Set it
to:

```
https://your-instance.com/api/v4/webhooks/slack
```

in each of these places that applies:

- **Slash Commands** — create a `/bg` command (and any others you want) with this Request URL.
- **Interactivity & Shortcuts** — turn on Interactivity and set the Request URL (needed for
  the **Acknowledge** / **Resolve** buttons on alerts).
- **Event Subscriptions** — if you enable events, set the Request URL here too.

<Callout type="info" title="Verify the URL after configuring credentials">
  Slack verifies the Request URL by sending a signed challenge that Nocturne validates with
  your <strong>Signing Secret</strong>. Configure the credentials in step 4 and restart
  <em>before</em> saving the URL, so verification passes.
</Callout>

## 6. Test it

1. From the workspace, run `/connect` (or your configured connect command) and complete the link.
2. Run `/bg` and confirm the latest reading comes back.
